Today, weâ€™re announcing new tools and programs to keep Instagram a safe and positive place for self-expression. Since the beginning, weâ€™ve tried to make Instagram a welcoming place for everyone. Our community has grown to 800 million, with 500 million using it every day. Itâ€™s more important than ever to strengthen our commitment to safety and kindness.

Comment Controls

Over time, weâ€™ve launched a number of tools to help you manage the comments experience, and today weâ€™re introducing more. Starting today, if your account is public, youâ€™ll see a new way to choose who can comment on your posts â€” from everyone to just groups of people, like people you follow or your followers. Also, whether your account is public or private, youâ€™ll be able to block other accounts from commenting on your posts. In June, we launched a filter to block certain offensive comments in English, today we are expanding this filter to Arabic, French, German and Portuguese. The filter will improve over time, enabling the communityâ€™s experience of sharing to improve as well. 
  
Anonymous Reporting for Live Video

Weâ€™re continuing to provide mental health resources to you when you need them most. If you see someone going through a difficult time or in need of support during a live broadcast, you can report it anonymously. The person will see a message offering help with options to talk to a helpline, reach out to a friend or get other tips and support. We have teams working 24 hours a day, seven days a week, around the world to respond.

Kindness Walls and Stickers

Over the next few months, weâ€™re turning walls in cities around the world into colorful murals inspiring #KindComments. Visit a wall, take a photo or video and share a #KindComment to make someoneâ€™s day. You can also participate by using a new kindness-themed heart-shaped sticker. Both the murals and stickers are created by artists from the global community. 

We feel as strongly about creating a safe and welcoming environment today as we did when our community was just getting started. To learn more about these tools and others, visit Instagram-Together.com. Thank you for being on this journey with us, and for taking care of each other. 

Kevin Systrom
Co-Founder & CEO

Many of you have told us that toxic comments discourage you from enjoying Instagram and expressing yourself freely. To help, weâ€™ve developed a filter that will block certain offensive comments on posts and in live video. You can turn this filter off in the â€œ...â€ settings menu from the profile and scroll to tap â€œComments.â€  Weâ€™ll launch this in English first, but will offer it in more languages over time. The spam filter removes any obvious spam in comments written in English, Spanish, Portuguese, Arabic, French, German, Russian, Japanese and Chinese.

These filters are powered by machine learning, trained by our team to recognize certain types of offensive and spammy comments so you never have to see them. They will improve over time, enabling the communityâ€™s experience to improve as well. 

Our work is far from finished and perfect, but I hope weâ€™re helping you feel safer and more welcome on Instagram.

Weekend Hashtag Project: #WHPhowicreate

The goal this weekend is to make photos and videos documenting your creative process â€” the why, the when and even the deeper question of how. San Francisco-based architect Dan Hogman (instagram.com/danhogman) tackles these questions during his sketching work: â€œArchitecture brings a sense of stability and timelessness,â€ he says. â€œBefore you get into the discussion on what it means or how it functions, a basic question is always current â€” how to represent it? How to capture the essence in just a few strokes, whether itâ€™s a single structure or a citywide scene,â€ says Dan, who makes daily drawings of settings and buildings that inspire him.

Hereâ€™s how to get started on your own submission this weekend: 

Document what happens when you sit down at the literal (or figurative) drawing board. When you put pen to paper â€” or brush to canvas â€” show what emerges, and how. 

Try exploring beyond what you might consider a typical creative process. How does a child line up her crayons? A bike repairman lay out his tools? Take note of the not-so-obvious creativity happening around you.

Experiment with different ways of capturing a creative process â€” like a Hyperlapse of a mural coming to life or a Boomerang of an artist at work in her studio.

Last September, we made a commitment to the community to keep Instagram a safe place for everyone. This year we will continue to act on that commitment and also focus on fostering kindness within our community.

The first step is to celebrate the kindness our community is already known for. On March 25 and 26, Instagrammers will come together for the kindness-themed Worldwide InstaMeet 15. Join an InstaMeet near you â€” or spread kindness by leaving an encouraging comment, giving an inspiring person a like or sharing a message of support with a friend.

As part of our goal to build a safe environment, we also have some updates to announce. Soon you may notice a screen over sensitive photos and videos when you scroll through your feed or visit a profile. While these posts donâ€™t violate our guidelines, someone in the community has reported them and our review team has confirmed they are sensitive. This change means you are less likely to have surprising or unwanted experiences in the app. If youâ€™d like to see a post that is covered with a screen, simply tap to reveal the photo or video. 

Our teams are focused on making Instagram a kind, welcoming place for everyone, and weâ€™re just getting started.

Kevin Systrom
Co-founder & CEO

The goal of this weekendâ€™s hashtag project is to photograph the places you or a fellow artist go to be creative. The project takes inspiration from London-based artist and guest curator Helen Downie (instagram.com/unskilledworker), best known for her fashion-inspired portraits and paintings.

Here are Helenâ€™s tips to get started:

Show off your unique studio space. â€œConcentrate on how important it is to have your own area â€” outside, inside, wherever, somewhere where you can just be,â€ says Helen. â€œI think that everybody needs that.â€

Photograph artists working, focusing on how different locations inspire people differently. â€œI sit in one chair to sketch. And then I go upstairs to a very small room to paint. And itâ€™s always the same,â€ Helen says. â€œItâ€™s just habit.â€

Experiment with Hyperlapse and Boomerang to capture the artistic process, whether a painting coming to life or behind the scenes of a photo shoot in video form.

PROJECT RULES: Please add the #WHPinthestudio hashtag only to photos and videos taken over this weekend and only submit your own visuals to the project. When Mike and I first created Instagram, we wanted it to be a welcoming community where people could share their lives. Images have the ability to inspire and bring out the best in us, whether they are funny, sad or beautiful. Over the past five years, Iâ€™ve watched in wonder as this community has grown to 500 million, with stories from every corner of the world. With this growth, we want to work diligently to maintain what has kept Instagram positive and safe, especially in the comments on your photos and videos.

The beauty of the Instagram community is the diversity of its members. All different types of people â€” from diverse backgrounds, races, genders, sexual orientations, abilities and more â€” call Instagram home, but sometimes the comments on their posts can be unkind. To empower each individual, we need to promote a culture where everyone feels safe to be themselves without criticism or harassment. Itâ€™s not only my personal wish to do this, I believe itâ€™s also our responsibility as a company. So, today, weâ€™re taking the next step to ensure Instagram remains a positive place to express yourself.

The first feature weâ€™re introducing is a keyword moderation tool that anyone can use. Now, when you tap the gear icon on your profile, youâ€™ll find a new Comments tool. This feature lets you list words you consider offensive or inappropriate. Comments containing these words will be hidden from your posts. You can choose your own list of words or use default words weâ€™ve provided. This is in addition to the tools weâ€™ve already developed such as swiping to delete comments, reporting inappropriate comments and blocking accounts.

We know tools arenâ€™t the only solution for this complex problem, but together we can work toward keeping Instagram a safe place for self-expression. My commitment to you is that we will keep building features that safeguard the community and maintain what makes Instagram a positive and creative place for everyone.

To learn more about comments on Instagram, check out the Instagram Help Center: https://help.instagram.com/700284123459336

Kevin Systrom
CEO & Co-founder, Instagram

Weekend Hashtag Project: #WHPilluminate
 
The goal this weekend is to make videos of interesting sources of light at night. Hereâ€™s how to get started:
 
Attend a fireworks show, concert or another event with large displays of moving or colorful lights. Try turning off your flash when you shoot to highlight the contrast between light and dark areas in your videos.
 
Try experimenting with a portable light source â€” like a sparkler, glow stick or flashlight â€” to create an interesting pattern for your video by moving the lights around in your frame.
 
Rather than shooting video of your light sources directly, try also looking around for subjects or areas the light is hitting in a striking way, like the flickering glow of a campfire on a friendâ€™s face.
 
PROJECT RULES: Please add the #WHPilluminate hashtag only to photos and videos taken over this weekend and only submit your own visuals to the project. If you include music in your video submissions, please only use music to which you own the rights. Any tagged photo or video taken over the weekend is eligible to be featured next week.

The goal this weekend is to make videos with interesting ambient (or natural) sound, like this one by @hummingbirdsxoxo. Hereâ€™s how to get started:

Close your eyes and let your ears lead you to your subject.
